elements.content: To investigate the influence of spatial extended direction and flexibility of secondary ligand on the resulting structure, eight new ferrocene-containing complexes with various dimensionalities have been synthesized by the reactions of CdII salts and 1,1′-bis(3-carboxy-1-oxopropyl)ferrocene (H2bfcs) with series of rationally selected N-heterocyclic spacers. When the small organic molecule 4-aminopyridine (apy) was employed as a secondary ligand, a one-dimensional (1D) linear complex {[Cd(bfcs)(apy)2]·H2O} n (1) was furnished, while the use of bis(azole) bridging ligands resulted in the formation of a 1D ribbon complex {[Cd(bfcs)(bbbm)1.5]·CH3OH·2H2O} n (2), a rare 1D quadruple-chain complex {[Cd(bfcs)(btmb)]·3H2O} n (3) and two two-dimensional (2D) puckered complexes {[Cd2(bfcs)2(pbbm)2]·2H2O} n (4) and {[Cd(bfcs)(bix)]·H2O} n (5) (bbbm = 1,1′-(1,4-butanediyl)bis-1H-benzimidazole, btmb = 4,4′-bis(1,2,4-triazole-1-ylmethyl)biphenyl, pbbm = 1,1′-(1,3-propanediyl)bis-1H-benzimidazole, bix = 1,4-bis(imidazole-1 -ylmethyl)benzene). In addition, the tripodal bridging secondary ligand led to an unusual three-dimensional (3D) layer pillar complex {[Cd2(bfcs)(titb)2Cl2]·2CH3OH·4H2O} n (6) (titb =1,3,5-tris(imidazol-1-ylmethyl)-2,4,6-trimethylbenzene). Employment of a flexible multidentate molecule tris(2-benzimidazolylmethyl)amine (ntb) as the secondary ligand gave birth to a mononuclear complex [Cd(bfcs)(ntb)]·DMF·5H2O (7) and a binuclear complex [Cd2(bfcs)(ntb)2]·bfcs·5H2O (8), in which ntb adopted the chelating coordination mode. It can be observed from the coordination architectures of 1−8 that secondary ligands had great effects on the spatial connective fashions of CdII centers, resulting in the formation of various dimensional complexes.

Introduction

The rational design and construction of novel metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) has been experiencing great growth in crystal engineering due to their structural diversities and potential applications as new materials. Up to now, many synthetic approaches have been applied to construct desired and attractive MOFs. In addition, the self-assembly method, using carefully selected metal centers as nodes and specially designed organic spacers as linkers, was proven to be an effective and successful synthetic strategy. Remarkable progress has been made on the theoretical analysis and practical manipulation based on such a self-assembly reaction, but the dimensionality control of the resulting complexes is still a great challenge at present, because the final structures are frequently modulated by various factors. It is well-known that organic spacers play crucial roles in the construction and structural tuning of the resulting MOFs. Changes in the type of bridging group, the flexibility of the molecular backbone, conformational preference, and spatial extended direction provided by the organic ligand can result in a remarkable class of complexes bearing diverse architectures and functions.

elements.content: In recent years, the two-ligand assembly system, consisting of two spacers and capable of providing more variability to build much more complicated and fascinating structures, has been widely adopted for the generation of new complexes. On the condition that one spacer (main ligand) and the metal center were fixed, the other spacer (secondary ligand) can be used as a structure-directing agent in such a reaction process and various dimensional (0D−3D) architectures, to some extent, could be purposefully obtained. However, due to the complexity and difficult prediction of the resulting composition or structure, the influential principles in a two-ligand system are still less ascertained and not conclusive. Therefore, the prospect of tuning the dimensionality of a complex through secondary ligand modification provides an impetus for further research on MOFs.

elements.content: In our present research, eight ferrocenyl carboxylate CdII complexes with a broad range of structures, including discrete zero-dimensional (0D) complexes, 1D linear, ribbonlike, and quadruple-chain structures, 2D puckered networks, and 3D layer pillar framework, were constructed by using series of N-heterocyclic molecules (Chart ) as secondary ligands. The influence of the spatial extended direction and flexibility of the N-heterocyclic ligands on the dimensionalities of these assembled complexes are also discussed in this paper. Additionally, the solid-state fluorescent spectra of these complexes, H2bfcs, and secondary ligands were measured at ambient temperature.

Elemental analyses (C, H, and N) were carried out on a FLASH EA 1112 elemental analyzer. The luminescent measurements for the solid samples were performed at room temperature using a HITACHI F-4500 fluorescence spectrophotometer. The excitation slit, as well as the emission slit was 2 nm. Thermal analyses were performed on a Netzsch STA 449C thermal analyzer from 30 to 700 °C at a heating rate of 10 °C⋅min-1 in air. elements.clean_text:
Results and Discussion

Design and Synthesis of Complexes

Recently, the topology and geometry control of the complexes has become one of the research emphases in coordination chemistry. The resulting structures are primarily dependent upon the coordination geometry of the metal center as well as the connective and regulative ability of the ligand. CdII ion, possessing diverse coordination geometries (five, six, seven-coordinated, etc.), is suitable for the construction of various coordination architectures. Moreover, the ligand containing carboxylate group also has a great ability to adopt different coordination modes and satisfy many metal coordination preferences, which will enrich the structural complexity of MOFs. Therefore, the combination of CdII ion and 1,1'-bis(3-carboxy-1-oxopropyl)ferrocene (H2bfcs) can bring the merits together, and then, various complexes with abundant structural diversity could be constructed.

elements.content: N-Heterocyclic spacers are known to be the versatile structural constructors which can bridge or chelate the metal ions to construct extended and discrete structures. Thereby, it may be feasible to tune the dimensionalities of the resulting complexes by introducing N-heterocyclic spacers as structure-directing agents into the CdII-bfcs systems. In our work, we first selected a small organic molecule 4-aminopyridine (apy) as the secondary ligand. As a result, a 1D linear complex {[Cd(bfcs)(apy)2]·H2O} n (1) with bfcs2- as the connector was obtained. The apy molecules, coordinating to the metal centers in terminal monodentate mode, did not show any effect on increasing the dimensionality of the resulting structure.

Thereby, it may be feasible to tune the dimensionalities of the resulting complexes by introducing N-heterocyclic spacers as structure-directing agents into the CdII-bfcs systems. In our work, we first selected a small organic molecule 4-aminopyridine (apy) as the secondary ligand. As a result, a 1D linear complex {[Cd(bfcs)(apy)2]⋅H2O} n  (1) with bfcs2- as the connector was obtained. The apy molecules, coordinating to the metal centers in terminal monodentate mode, did not show any effect on increasing the dimensionality of the resulting structure.

elements.content: Organic bridging ligand, which is capable of linking two or more metal centers, can extend the structures to multidimensional networks in definite direction. So, we selected four kinds of bis(azole) molecules with different coordination groups and flexibility as the secondary ligands, intending to observe their effects on the assembly of complexes. To hold the energetic minimum, the flexible nature of spacers allowed them to bend and rotate when they coordinated to metal centers; hence, a 1D ribbon complex {[Cd(bfcs)(bbbm)1.5]·CH3OH·2H2O} n (2), a 1D quadruple-chain complex {[Cd(bfcs)(btmb)]·3H2O} n (3), and two 2D puckered grid-like complexes {[Cd2(bfcs)2(pbbm)2]·2H2O} n (4), and {[Cd(bfcs)(bix)]·H2O} n (5) were constructed. The diverse dimensionalities (1D or 2D) of the four complexes could be traced back to the dissimilar backbone flexibility of the four bis(azole) secondary ligands. The butyl of bbbm and biphenyl of btmb, which were more flexible than relative propyl of pbbm and phenyl of bix, can rotate and bend more freely and the conformational freedom engendered various topologies, which were structurally less predictable. Furthermore, 2D complexes 4 and 5 could be described as resulting from the structural transformation of 1D complex 1, by replacing the terminally coordinated ligand with bridging ligand.

elements.content: Considering that the bis(azole) molecule has only two coordination groups that limited its spatial extended direction, we then employed tripodal N-heterocyclic ligand titb with three functional groups, providing more potential coordination sites and extended directions, to construct an even more fascinating complex with higher dimensionality. As a result, an unusual 3D layer pillar complex {[Cd2(bfcs)(titb)2Cl2]·2CH3OH·4H2O} n (6) was successfully constructed. In this complex, the titb molecules, acting as 3-connected ligands, linked the CdII centers to extend in a 2D layer, and such layers were further connected together by bfcs2- ligands.

When the flexible multidentate molecule ntb was employed as the secondary ligand, two discrete 0D complexes [Cd(bfcs)(ntb)]·DMF·5H2O (7) and [Cd2(bfcs)(ntb)2]·bfcs·5H2O (8) were furnished owing to the chelating effect of ntb, which terminated the dimensional extension.

elements.content: It can be observed that the results confirmed the feasibility of the foregoing idea using specially selected organic spacers as structure-directing agents to tune the dimensionalities of the complexes in a two-ligand system. Further insight into understand the effects of secondary ligands on the dimensionalities of complexes 1−8 could be perspicuously envisaged by describing the main ligand (bfcs2-) as a “Line” and the secondary ligands 4-aminopyridine, bis(azole) bridging, and tripodal bridging molecules as “point”, “line”, and “plane”, respectively. The combination of “Line” and “point” resulted in the formation of a simple 1D linear complex 1, combination of “Line” and “line” resulted in two 1D multichain complexes (2, 3) and two 2D grid-like complexes (4, 5), and the combination of “Line” and “plane” led to a 3D layer pillar complex 6. The flexible multidentate molecule ntb was like a “cap” when it adopted the chelating coordination mode, and so, two 0D complexes (7, 8) were furnished through the combination of “Line” and “cap”. The strategy of dimensionality control implemented by the modification of secondary N-heterocyclic ligands could be schematically shown by Chart .

elements.content: Crystallographic analysis reveals that complex 2 crystallizes in the triclinic space group P1̅. The CdII center is seven-coordinated in a distorted pentagonal-bipyramidal geometry, defined by O1, O2, O4, and O5 from two bfcs2- and N3 from a bbbm ligand in the equatorial plane, and N1, N5 arising from two other bbbm ligands in the axial position (Figure a), and the Cd−O and Cd−N distances vary from 2.348(5) to 2.584(5) Å and 2.373(5) to 2.383(5) Å, respectively. Each seven-coordinated CdII has a distorted pentagonal-bipyramidal geometry, in which two btmb position-4 N donors occupy the axial position with the Cd−N distances of 2.299(3) and 2.332(3) Å, while five O atoms from three bfcs2- ligands constitute the pentagonal plane with the Cd−O distances from 2.355(3) to 2.615(4) Å. It can be clearly seen from Figure a that, within the binuclear unit, two CdII ions are bridged by two carboxylate O atoms (O3A, O3B) forming a Cd2O2 ring with the Cd···Cd distance of 3.850 Å. Such Cd2O2 units are linked together by pairs of bfcs2- and btmb ligands to form an infrequent 1D quadruple chain (Figure b). The triazole groups of btmb are in cis conformation (Figure ) with the dihedral angles of 62.53° and 89.13° between the planes of triazole ring and adjacent benzene ring, and the dihedral angles of two benzene ring planes and two triazole ring planes are 33.17° and 37.71°, respectively. To the best of our knowledge, although many 1D chain complexes have been reported, such 1D quadruple-chain structure was comparatively scarce. It is worth noting that, in this complex, the bfcs2- ligand displays a different coordination mode from those of the above complexes; two carboxylate groups of the bfcs2- ligand adopt bidentate chelating and bidentate chelating/bridging modes, respectively.

elements.content: The 2D complex 4 crystallizes in the chiral space group P1, and contains two crystallographically different CdII centers. They exhibit similar coordination geometries except that the bond lengths and bond angles around them are different. So, only the coordination environment around Cd1 is illustrated in this paper. As can be seen from Figure a, the octahedral arrangement {CdN2O4} around the CdII center is completed by four carboxylate O atoms from two different bfcs2- anions and two N atoms from two pbbm ligands. Both the pbbm molecules show TT conformation with the torsion angles of 175.80° and 164.38° for N1 containing pbbm and 164.69° and 173.29° for N5 containing pbbm, respectively (Figure ). The Cd−O distances range from 2.333(7) to 2.510(8) Å and the bond distances of Cd−N are 2.270(8) and 2.323(7) Å. The bfcs2- links CdII ions in bis-chelating mode to form a Cd-bfcs helical chain, and the connection of TT pbbm ligands with CdII ions can also be described as an infinite 1D helical chain (Figure b). These 1D helical chains, repeating in a ···ABAB··· stacking sequence in crystallographic ab plane, are joined together by sharing CdII centers to form a 2D network (Figure ). A better insight into the nature of the involved network can be achieved by the application of a topological exhibition. By the standing of blue stick for pbbm and yellow stick for bfcs2-, the 2D grid structure can be topologically represented as shown in Figure c. Each Cd1(2) occupies the top position of a square-based pyramid, in which the bottom plane is formed by four adjacent coplanar Cd2(1), and the Cd···Cd separations around each CdII center are 9.815(2), 9.677(2), 8.927(2), and 8.857(2) Å. So, CdII can be regarded as a 4-connected node, and the whole structure is extended to a noninterpenetrated puckered network (Figure ) by the connection of bfcs2- and the secondary ligand pbbm.

elements.content: A single-crystal X-ray diffraction study reveals that complex 5 crystallizes in the triclinic space group P1̅ and features a 2D puckered network. As shown in Figure a, the coordination sphere of each CdII ion in 5 is defined in a six-coordinated environment supplied by two nitrogen atoms from two bix ligands and four oxygen atoms from two bfcs2- ligands. The bond distances of Cd−N are 2.249(3) and 2.267(3) Å, which are obviously shorter than the corresponding bond lengths of 1D complexes 2 and 3, and the Cd−O distances ranging from 2.286(2) to 2.478(3) Å are comparable to those of the above complexes. The CdII ions are linked by the bfcs2- ligands to form a 1D chain with the Cd···Cd separation of 12.1 Å, and such linear chains are further joined together to form a 2D puckered grid-like network by two kinds of bix ligands (Figure b). Both kinds of the bix ligands adopt trans conformation (Figure ) and the imidazole rings of each bix are parallel to each other. However, the dihedral angles between the planes of imidazole ring and benzene ring in these two kinds of bix ligands are different. The dihedral angles are 79.92° for N1 containing bix or 77.01° for N3 containing bix, and the Cd···Cd distances separated by these two kinds of bix are also different (14.5 Å or 15.8 Å). That is to say, four CdII ions, two bfcs2- ligands, and two bix ligands construct two types of rhomboid lattices with the large window of 12.1 × 14.5 Å2 (the interior angles of 109.43° and 70.57°) or 12.1 × 15.8 Å2 (the interior angles of 146.2° and 33.8°). In this complex, the bfcs2- ligands adopt the bis-chelating coordination mode to link metal centers, which is identical to those of complexes 1, 2, and 4. The 2D puckered network of 5 is schematically shown in Figure c (regarding the metal ions as nodes and bridging ligands as linkers).

elements.content: The crystal structure analysis demonstrates that 6 crystallizes in the monoclinic space group C2c, which is identical with that of complex 3. Each CdII ion is five-coordinated, and one bis-monodentate bridging bfcs2- oxygen atom (Cd−O 2.293(3) Å), a chlorine ion (Cd−Cl 2.5228(18) Å), together with three titb nitrogen atoms (Cd−N 2.303(4)−2.323(4) Å) complete the CdN3OCl trigonal-bipyramidal geometry (Figure a). It is interesting that, in this complex, all titb ligands are in cis,trans,trans-conformation with respect to the orientation of the imidazole groups and the central trimethylbenzene ring. As shown in Figure , the imidazole ring 1 (N5, C24, C25, N6, C26) lies to one side of the trimethylbenzene plane, while the other two rings 2 (N1, C10, C11, N2, C12) and 3 (N3, C28, C29, N4, C30) are on the opposite side, resulting in a capital “Y”. Ring 1 is inclined to the trimethylbenzene ring with angle of 65.92°, and the values are 79.57° and 83.60° for ring 2 and ring 3. The dihedral angles between rings 1 and 2, rings 1 and 3, rings 2 and 3 are 72.48°, 31.45°, and 56.84°, respectively. Each titb, acting as a 3-connected ligand, is ligated to three different CdII via the nitrogen atoms of the three imidazole groups to form a 2D network (Figure b) containing the combination of (ML)4 and (ML)2 rings (M = CdII, L = titb). These 2D layers are further connected by bfcs2- ligands (acting as bridging pillars) to build a 3D layer pillar framework (Figure c). Further topological analyses performed by the OLEX program indicate that the framework of 6 could be classified as a (4·6·8)(4·62·83) topological type if we defined tripodal titb, CdII as 3-, 4-connected nodes, respectively. The layer pillar structure can be schematically represented by Figure . Most interestingly, within each 2D layer, there exist alternant left- and right-handed helical chains (Figure ) which are formed by titb ligands bridging CdII ions. It is noticeable that such 3D framework based on the organometallic group of ferrocene has rarely been reported before, despite the common occurrence of 3D layer pillar complexes in coordination chemistry.

elements.content: In these complexes, the completely deprotonated H2bfcs adopt various coordination modes (Scheme ) to satisfy many coordination preferences and facilitate the formation of particular complexes. For example, the presence of tridentate-bridging carboxylate group (μ2-η2-O2C−) in complex 3 leads to a quadruple-chain structure by linking two double-chain components together. In complex 6, it is possible that the ferrocenyl carboxylate in bis-monodentate mode permits more imidazole groups of titb to coordinate to the CdII centers; accordingly, the structure could be extended along more directions. The formation of mononuclear complex 7 can be regarded as a result of the existence of an uncoordinated carboxylate group besides the effect of chelating ntb. Conclusions

In summary, by taking advantage of systemic N-heterocyclic organic molecules as secondary ligands, eight novel complexes, ranging from discrete 0D molecular architectures to infinite 1D, 2D, and 3D complexes were successfully constructed. The resulting structures demonstrate nicely how the secondary ligands orient themselves in different conformations to facilitate the formation of distinctly different interaction hierarchies. The secondary ligands, therefore, can be used as structure-directing agents to control and tune the dimensionalities of the resulting frameworks in a two-ligand assembly process on the condition that the main ligand and metal center were fixed.

The thermostability of complexes 1−8 was estimated by thermogravimetric analysis (TGA), which indicated that solvent molecules were continuously removed before about 180 °C in these complexes. The major weight losses were observed in the range of about 240−530 °C except for 3 and 6 (the final weight losses continued up to about 640 °C), corresponding to the decomposition of networks (Figure ). In addition, the PXRD patterns were recorded for all complexes, and they were comparable to the corresponding simulated ones calculated from the single-crystal diffraction data (as shown in Figure ), indicating a pure phase of each bulky sample.

Fluorescent Properties

The solid-state fluorescent spectra of 1−8, secondary ligands, and H2bfcs were measured at ambient temperature, and the emission maxima and excitation wavelengths are listed in Table . The entire complexes exhibit similar weak emissions with maximum intensity at about 558 nm upon excitation at 410 nm. These emissions might be tentatively assigned to the intraligand fluorescent emission of bfcs2-, because a similar emission at 539 nm upon excitation at 396 nm is also observed for the free H2bfcs. Moreover, the fluorescent spectra of all complexes exhibit a slight red-shift in contrast to free H2bfcs. This is probably because the coordination of the deprotonated H2bfcs to CdII ions results in a change in the energy levels of bfcs2-.
